---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "The Complete Guide to Building a Gaming PC (2026)",
      "description": "Everything about building a gaming PC: component selection, GPU benchmarks, bottleneck analysis, budget tiers, and step-by-step assembly.",
      "image": "https://leeroyjenkins.quest/og-image.jpg",
      "author": {
        "@type": "Person",
        "name": "Leeroy Jenkins"
      },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Leeroy Jenkins",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://leeroyjenkins.quest/logo.png"
        }
      },
      "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
      "dateModified": "2026-01-01"
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the best GPU for gaming in 2026?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The best GPU depends on your budget and target resolution. For 1080p, the RTX 4060 or RX 7600 are great. For 1440p, look at the RTX 4070 Super or RX 7800 XT. For 4K, the RTX 4080 Super or RTX 4090 are top-tier."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do I check for a CPU or GPU bottleneck?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "You can use monitoring software like MSI Afterburner. If your GPU utilization is at 95-100% and your CPU is much lower, you are GPU bound (ideal for gaming). If your CPU is near 100% while your GPU is underutilized, you have a CPU bottleneck."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How much RAM do I need for gaming?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "16GB is the absolute minimum for modern gaming. However, 32GB is strongly recommended for a smooth experience in new AAA titles, multi-tasking, or gaming while having browser tabs open."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Do I need liquid cooling for my CPU?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Not necessarily. High-end air coolers perform exceptionally well and are often cheaper and more reliable than liquid coolers. However, for top-tier CPUs like the Intel Core i9 or Ryzen 9, a 280mm or 360mm AIO liquid cooler is recommended to prevent thermal throttling."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I build a good gaming PC for $500?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, but it requires compromises. At $500, you will likely be looking at entry-level GPUs, older generation parts, or CPUs with strong integrated graphics like AMD's APUs for 1080p low-to-medium settings."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="leeroyjenkins"
  title="The Complete Guide to Building a Gaming PC (2026)"
  description="Everything about building a gaming PC: component selection, GPU benchmarks, bottleneck analysis, budget tiers, and step-by-step assembly."
  canonical="https://leeroyjenkins.quest/guide-gaming-pc-complete"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-5 py-12">
    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="mb-12 text-center">
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black mb-4 text-transparent bg-clip-text bg-gradient-to-br from-white to-[var(--accent-color)] tracking-tight">
        The Complete Guide to Building a Gaming PC (2026)
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
        Everything you need to know about component selection, avoiding bottlenecks, budget tiers, and assembling your dream setup.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Navigation Menu (TOC) -->
    <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 mb-12 shadow-lg">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Table of Contents</h2>
      <ul class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)] font-medium">
        <li><a href="#why-build" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">1. Why Build Your Own PC?</a></li>
        <li><a href="#understanding-components" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">2. Understanding Components</a></li>
        <li><a href="#gpu-selection" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">3. GPU Selection Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="#bottlenecking" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">4. CPU & GPU Bottlenecking</a></li>
        <li><a href="#budget-tiers" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">5. Budget Tiers ($500 - $2000+)</a></li>
        <li><a href="#assembly" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">6. Step-by-Step Assembly</a></li>
        <li><a href="#optimizing-fps" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">7. Optimizing FPS</a></li>
        <li><a href="#faq" class="hover:text-[var(--accent-color)] transition-colors">8. Frequently Asked Questions</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Content Sections -->
    <div class="space-y-16">
      <!-- 1. Why Build Your Own PC? -->
      <section id="why-build">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">1. Why Build Your Own PC?</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">
            Building a PC instead of buying a pre-built system is a rite of passage for PC gamers. While pre-builts offer convenience, building your own system brings several undeniable advantages:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-4">
            <li><strong>Cost Savings:</strong> You avoid the "builder's tax". The premium you pay for assembly can instead go directly into a better <a href="/gpu-performance-index" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Graphics Card</a> or CPU.</li>
            <li><strong>Customization:</strong> You choose every single part. You aren't stuck with a proprietary motherboard or a low-quality power supply hidden inside a flashy case.</li>
            <li><strong>Upgradability:</strong> Custom builds use standard parts. When it's time for an upgrade, you can swap out individual components without needing to replace the entire system.</li>
            <li><strong>The Experience:</strong> There is a unique satisfaction in putting together the components, managing the cables, and pressing the power button for the first time.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 2. Understanding Components -->
      <section id="understanding-components">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">2. Understanding Components</h2>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">CPU (Processor)</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] text-sm">The brain of your PC. It handles game logic, physics, AI, and telling the GPU what to draw. Essential for maintaining high framerates at 1080p.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">GPU (Graphics Card)</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] text-sm">The most important part of a gaming PC. It renders the graphics, textures, and lighting you see on screen. It dictates what resolution and settings you can play at.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">RAM (Memory)</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] text-sm">Fast, short-term memory where the CPU stores data it needs right now (like game assets). 16GB is the minimum, but 32GB is the new standard.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">Storage (SSD)</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] text-sm">Where your games are permanently saved. NVMe SSDs are crucial for modern gaming to ensure fast load times and texture streaming.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">Motherboard</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] text-sm">The nervous system that connects everything together. It dictates what CPUs you can use and how many connections (USB, M.2) you have.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-5 rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-2">PSU (Power Supply)</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] text-sm">Provides power to your components. Never cheap out on this. Get a reliable 80+ Bronze or Gold rated unit from a reputable brand.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 3. GPU Selection Guide -->
      <section id="gpu-selection">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">3. GPU Selection Guide</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">
            Selecting a GPU is the most critical decision in your build. It determines your target resolution and graphical settings. Check out our <a href="/gpu-performance-index" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">GPU Performance Index</a> for detailed rankings.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-6 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-color)] mb-6">
            <h4 class="text-white font-bold mb-3">Targeting Resolutions:</h4>
            <ul class="space-y-3">
              <li><span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] font-bold">1080p Gaming:</span> Ideal for competitive shooters. Look at the NVIDIA RTX 4060 or AMD Radeon RX 7600.</li>
              <li><span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] font-bold">1440p Gaming:</span> The sweet spot for visuals and performance. The RTX 4070 Super or RX 7800 XT are excellent choices.</li>
              <li><span class="text-[var(--accent-color)] font-bold">4K Gaming:</span> Requires serious horsepower. You'll need at least an RTX 4080 Super or RX 7900 XTX.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p>
            <strong>VRAM Matters:</strong> Modern games are demanding more Video RAM. Try to aim for at least 12GB of VRAM if you plan to play at 1440p or above to avoid stuttering as textures load.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 4. CPU & GPU Bottlenecking -->
      <section id="bottlenecking">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">4. CPU & GPU Bottlenecking</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">
            A "bottleneck" occurs when one component limits the maximum performance of another. In a perfectly balanced gaming PC, your GPU should run at near 100% utilization. If it isn't, something else (usually the CPU) is holding it back.
          </p>
          <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 mb-6">
            <div class="flex-1 bg-red-900/20 border border-red-900/50 p-4 rounded-lg">
              <h4 class="text-red-400 font-bold mb-2">CPU Bottleneck</h4>
              <p class="text-sm">The CPU can't process game logic fast enough to feed frames to the GPU. Result: Stuttering and lower FPS than the GPU is capable of. Common at 1080p.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1 bg-green-900/20 border border-green-900/50 p-4 rounded-lg">
              <h4 class="text-green-400 font-bold mb-2">GPU Bottleneck</h4>
              <p class="text-sm">The GPU is working as hard as it can (99% usage). This is the <strong>ideal scenario</strong> for a gaming PC. It means you are getting everything you paid for out of your graphics card.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>
            To ensure your components are well-matched, use our <a href="/bottleneck-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Bottleneck Calculator</a> or read how different <a href="/game-engine-comparison" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">game engines utilize hardware</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 5. Budget Tiers -->
      <section id="budget-tiers">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">5. Budget Tiers</h2>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-6">
          Not sure how to allocate your funds? Use our interactive <a href="/gaming-pc-builder" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Gaming PC Builder tool</a> or use these quick templates:
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="p-5 font-bold text-white text-lg flex justify-between items-center bg-[var(--bg-color)] rounded-t-lg border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">
              <span>$500 Tier (Entry Level / 1080p)</span>
            </h3>
            <div class="p-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
              <p class="mb-2">Aimed at eSports titles and older games at 1080p.</p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 text-sm">
                <li>CPU: AMD Ryzen 5 5600G (Integrated Graphics) or Intel Core i3</li>
                <li>GPU: Rely on APU or used market (e.g., used RX 6600)</li>
                <li>RAM: 16GB DDR4 3200MHz</li>
                <li>Storage: 500GB NVMe SSD</li>
                <li>PSU: 500W 80+ Bronze</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="p-5 font-bold text-white text-lg flex justify-between items-center bg-[var(--bg-color)] rounded-t-lg border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">
              <span>$1,000 Tier (Solid 1080p / Entry 1440p)</span>
            </h3>
            <div class="p-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
              <p class="mb-2">The most popular tier. Handles modern AAA games well.</p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 text-sm">
                <li>CPU: AMD Ryzen 5 7600 or Intel Core i5-13400F</li>
                <li>GPU: AMD Radeon RX 7600 XT or NVIDIA RTX 4060</li>
                <li>RAM: 32GB DDR5 6000MHz</li>
                <li>Storage: 1TB NVMe SSD</li>
                <li>PSU: 650W 80+ Gold</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="p-5 font-bold text-white text-lg flex justify-between items-center bg-[var(--bg-color)] rounded-t-lg border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">
              <span>$1,500 Tier (The Sweet Spot / High 1440p)</span>
            </h3>
            <div class="p-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
              <p class="mb-2">Excellent performance without severe diminishing returns.</p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 text-sm">
                <li>CPU: AMD Ryzen 7 7800X3D (Best gaming CPU)</li>
                <li>GPU: NVIDIA RTX 4070 Super or AMD Radeon RX 7800 XT</li>
                <li>RAM: 32GB DDR5 6000MHz CL30</li>
                <li>Storage: 2TB NVMe SSD</li>
                <li>PSU: 750W 80+ Gold</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-lg">
            <h3 class="p-5 font-bold text-white text-lg flex justify-between items-center bg-[var(--bg-color)] rounded-t-lg border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">
              <span>$2,000+ Tier (Enthusiast 4K)</span>
            </h3>
            <div class="p-5 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
              <p class="mb-2">No compromises. High refresh rate 4K gaming.</p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 text-sm">
                <li>CPU: AMD Ryzen 7 7800X3D or Intel Core i7-14700K</li>
                <li>GPU: NVIDIA RTX 4080 Super or RTX 4090</li>
                <li>RAM: 32GB or 64GB DDR5 6000MHz CL30</li>
                <li>Storage: 2TB or 4TB High-End NVMe Gen4/Gen5</li>
                <li>PSU: 850W or 1000W 80+ Gold/Platinum</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 6. Step-by-Step Assembly -->
      <section id="assembly">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">6. Step-by-Step Assembly</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-4">
            <li>
              <strong class="text-white">Prep the Motherboard Outside the Case:</strong>
              Place the motherboard on its cardboard box. Install the CPU (be careful with the pins!), slot in the RAM sticks (usually in slots 2 and 4), and install your M.2 NVMe SSD.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-white">Install the CPU Cooler:</strong>
              If using an air cooler, install the mounting bracket and the cooler now. If using a large AIO liquid cooler, you might want to wait until the motherboard is in the case.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-white">Prepare the Case & Install Power Supply:</strong>
              Install the I/O shield (if not pre-installed on the motherboard) into the back of the case. Slide the PSU into its basement compartment and route the necessary cables to the back panel.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-white">Mount the Motherboard:</strong>
              Carefully lower the motherboard into the case onto the standoffs and screw it down.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-white">Front Panel & Power Connections:</strong>
              Connect the tiny front panel connectors (power button, reset switch), USB headers, and audio. Then connect the 24-pin motherboard power and 8-pin CPU power cables from the PSU.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-white">Install the GPU:</strong>
              Remove the PCIe covers on the back of the case. Slot the GPU into the top PCIe x16 slot until it clicks. Screw it securely to the case and attach its power cables.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-white">Cable Management & First Boot:</strong>
              Tidy up cables in the back to ensure the side panel closes. Plug the PC into the wall, connect a <a href="/guide-monitor-buying" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">gaming monitor</a> to the GPU (not the motherboard!), and hit the power button.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 7. Optimizing FPS -->
      <section id="optimizing-fps">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">7. Optimizing FPS</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">
            Building the PC is only half the battle. To ensure you are getting the frames you deserve, you need to configure your software correctly. See our full <a href="/guide-fps-optimization" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">FPS Optimization Guide</a> for a deep dive, or follow these quick tips:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
            <li><strong>Enable XMP/EXPO in BIOS:</strong> RAM runs at slow baseline speeds out of the box. You must enable XMP (Intel) or EXPO (AMD) in your BIOS to get the advertised speeds (e.g., 6000MHz).</li>
            <li><strong>Update GPU Drivers:</strong> Download the latest drivers directly from NVIDIA (GeForce Experience/App) or AMD (Adrenalin Edition).</li>
            <li><strong>Monitor Refresh Rate:</strong> Right-click your desktop &rarr; Display Settings &rarr; Advanced Display. Make sure your monitor is actually set to 144Hz, 240Hz, etc.</li>
            <li><strong>In-Game Settings:</strong> Use upscaling tech like DLSS (NVIDIA) or FSR (AMD) to boost FPS. You can estimate potential framerates with our <a href="/fps-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">FPS Calculator</a> or check <a href="/game-fps-data" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline">Game FPS Data</a>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 8. FAQ -->
      <section id="faq">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-2">8. Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">What is the best GPU for gaming in 2026?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">The best GPU depends on your budget and target resolution. For 1080p, the RTX 4060 or RX 7600 are great. For 1440p, look at the RTX 4070 Super or RX 7800 XT. For 4K, the RTX 4080 Super or RTX 4090 are top-tier.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How do I check for a CPU or GPU bottleneck?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">You can use monitoring software like MSI Afterburner. If your GPU utilization is at 95-100% and your CPU is much lower, you are GPU bound (ideal for gaming). If your CPU is near 100% while your GPU is underutilized, you have a CPU bottleneck.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How much RAM do I need for gaming?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">16GB is the absolute minimum for modern gaming. However, 32GB is strongly recommended for a smooth experience in new AAA titles, multi-tasking, or gaming while having browser tabs open.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Do I need liquid cooling for my CPU?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Not necessarily. High-end air coolers perform exceptionally well and are often cheaper and more reliable than liquid coolers. However, for top-tier CPUs like the Intel Core i9 or Ryzen 9, a 280mm or 360mm AIO liquid cooler is recommended to prevent thermal throttling.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Can I build a good gaming PC for $500?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Yes, but it requires compromises. At $500, you will likely be looking at entry-level GPUs, older generation parts, or CPUs with strong integrated graphics like AMD's APUs for 1080p low-to-medium settings.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
